column4: The ancient Egyptian social structure was characterized by rigid social classes that dictated the opportunities available to people at different levels of society. Nobles held the highest political and economic power, profiting from tributes paid to the pharaoh. Priests were responsible for pleasing the gods, while soldiers were responsible for supervising the peasants, farmers and slaves involved in building the monumental structures such as the pyramids and palaces. Skilled workers, including doctors and craftsmen, formed the middle class. The lowest social class, consisting of slaves and farmers, faced dire circumstances and a life of servitude.  The social structure allowed the pharaoh to exert absolute power over his subjects and to rely on nobles and wealthy individuals to collect taxes on their behalf. The vizier, acting as the tax collector, ensured that taxes were paid, while the nobles were responsible for holding government positions and profiting from tax collections. Skilled workers contributed to the economy through their craftsmanship and trade, enriching the social elite. On the other hand, the lowest social class, consisting of slaves and farmers, were deprived of opportunities for social mobility and faced a challenging existence.

column3: An ideal tragedy follows a relatable protagnist. This character is flawed and down to earth in order for the audience to truly empathize with the hero's fatal flaw and sympathize with their great downfall. The plot of the story should follow the hero's fall from grace as a result of their behavior and the advancement of a heinous villain. The protagonist begins the story with good luck, then ends it with bad luck (and vice versa, in the antagonist's case). The most vital aspect of a tragedy is its ending. Tragedies must end unhappily. The hero must suffer a horrible ending and the villain is encouraged to prosper (or at least to win). This is to arouse deep seated feelings of fear and pity in the audience, feelings that they are usually disconnected with and tragedies were created to help the audience regulate their (often repressed) negativity by connecting with and learning from the protagonist's fate.
column4: Sure, here is the rewritten passage:  An ideal tragedy follows a relatable protagonist. This character is flawed and down to earth, mirroring the hero's fatal flaw. The plot unfolds as the hero's downfall is propelled by the villain's advancement and bad choices. Starting with good fortune, the protagonist ends tragically with misfortune or vice versa. The essence of a tragedy lies in its concluding moments. Tragic endings depict a protagonist's suffering, while the antagonist's triumph fosters a sense of fear and pity in the audience. These emotional responses are meant to resonate on a personal level, offering audiences a means to process and learn from the protagonist's experience.

column3: The factory used various ways to use and cover up spoiled meat. For example, when the meat would become spoiled they would "rub it up with soda to take away the smell" (Source 1). They used this in order to continue selling this spoiled meat despite the fact that it was unhealth. The factory would just take away the smell to cover up the fact that it was old. Continuing, whenever Europe would send back "old sausage that had been rejected, and that was moldy and white – it would be dosed with borax and glycerin" (Source 1) so that it could be sent back out. They ensured that they weren't losing money on this dirty, old sausag. By using chemicals they could still use the spoiled meat. Moreover, the factory stored barrels and "the barrels would be dirt and rust and old nails and stale water – and cartload after cartload of it would be taken up and dumped into the hoppers with fresh meat" (Source 1). This would happen once a year, meaning this meat and grime would sit for a year and then they would sell it to the people. They didn't care about anything but getting the money from this soiled meat. The factory would do anything and put any chemical or trick on the meat in order to use or cover up the spoiled meat.
column4: The factory employed a range of deceitful and manipulative practices to hide the truth about the spoiled meat they produced. One common method employed was to rub the spoiled meat with soda, masking the unpleasant smell with a chemical disguise. Another tactic was to add borax and glycerin to contaminated sausages, disguising the smell and ensuring that the meat could be sent back to Europe. The factory also stored spoiled meat in barrels, allowing it to sit for a year before being sold. This practice allowed the factory to maintain the illusion that the meat was fresh while it was actually spoiled.

column3: The Third Wave was an experiment set up by a high school teacher to show his students "how people throughout history followed the crowd even when terrible things were happening" (paragraph 1). However, Mr. Jones told the students that it was a movement aimed to eliminate democracy, and "that democracy’s main weakness is that it favors the individual over the whole community" (paragraph 1). Jones forced conformity among the students by drilling things like proper seating and emerging as an authoritarian figure. It was meant to be a one-day experiment, but it ended up lasting a whole week. Jones made up a salute resembling the Nazis and ordered the students to salute to each other even outside of class. Over the week, the experiment expanded from 30 students to 200! By the end of the week, Jones felt the experiment was getting out of hand, so he tricked the students and then explained that "they had been a part of an experiment to demonstrate how people willingly create a sense of superiority over others, and how this can lead people to justify doing horrible things in the name of the state’s honor" (paragraph 5).
column4: Sure, here is the rewritten passage:  The Third Wave experiment was a pedagogical experiment designed to illustrate the concept of people following the crowd, even when facing terrible circumstances. Mr. Jones, a teacher, presented a captivating argument, claiming that democracy's core flaw is prioritizing individual rights over the collective good. He enforced conformity by dictating seating arrangements and encouraging students to adhere to a specific posture during class. The experiment's initial intent was short-lived, lasting a full week. To ensure the safety of both students and school personnel, Jones resorted to manipulation tactics and eventually fabricated an argument that resonated with the students. This fabricated explanation deconstructed the true purpose of the experiment, ultimately leading to the conclusion that people willingly engage in narcissistic behavior to secure their place within their society's hierarchy and justify inhumane actions in the name of their country.

column3: The factory had many discusting ways in which it would cover up spoiled meat. For example, they would "fix" spoiled meat by loading it with chemicals to get rid of the mold and smell. "There was never the least attention paid to what was cut up for sausage; there would come all the way back from Europe old sausage that had been rejected, and that was moldy and white – it would be dosed with borax and glycerin, and dumped into the hoppers, and made over again for home consumption." They would also use every part of the animal they could, including non-meat parts, and make things such as "head cheese" with old hogs which had been cooked and chpped finely. And, in addition to loading these nasty spoled meats with chemicals, the factory would use marketing schemes to make the meat seem more interesting. Things such as "California hams," and "smoked" sausage which were really just more moldy meat made to look or sound a certain way that would be appealing towards the customer.
column4: The factory implemented various deceitful methods to conceal spoiled meats. They employed a technique known as "fixing" spoiled meat, which involved introducing chemicals to suppress mold and odor. The practice resulted in the intentional addition of contaminated old sausage from Europe, which had gone through a decline in quality due to an excessive amount of mold. This mold was removed and replaced with borax and glycerin, before being redistributed for home consumption.  Instead of discarding these contaminated meats, the factory sought to reanimate them by transforming them into unusual and enticing products. They crafted various preparations using non-meat parts, such as "head cheese" from aged hogs and smoked sausage that lacked the characteristic smoky flavor. Furthermore, marketing campaigns were executed to mimic popular trends, such as California hams and smoked sausages that resembled their traditional counterparts but were actually contaminated with mold.
